{
  "id": "019d3424-5d56-75a3-9493-5ff58377d57e",
  "content": "# Multi-Spoke Phase 0 Complete (2026-03-28)\n\n## What: MCP bearer token auth + spoke Dockerfile shipped as foundation for multi-spoke workspace\n\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Token-gated writes: 8 tools protected (corvia_write, gc_run, config_set, rebuild_index, agent_suspend, merge_retry, pin, unpin). Reads stay open.\n2. Token reused across restarts: existing mcp-token file is loaded on startup instead of regenerating. Prevents spoke invalidation on hub restart.\n3. Constant-time comparison: XOR-based byte comparison prevents timing side-channel attacks on token validation.\n4. File permissions: mcp-token written with 0600 (owner-only) on Unix systems.\n5. Loopback detection via IpAddr::is_loopback() instead of string matching. Handles IPv6 correctly.\n6. Spoke Dockerfile: node:22-bookworm, non-root user, pinned Claude Code, no build-essential (~200MB savings).\n7. Entrypoint: .mcp.json written to ~/.claude/ (not workspace) to prevent token leakage via git commits.\n8. Error code: UNAUTHORIZED (-32001) distinct from SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE (-32000).\n9. JSON construction in entrypoint uses jq to prevent injection via error messages.\n\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- std::fs::write() uses process umask (typically 0644). Always set_permissions(0o600) for secrets.\n- Token regeneration on restart silently breaks connected clients. Persist and reuse tokens.\n- Shell parameter expansion ${URL##*/} only strips to last slash, not owner/repo. Use sed for GitHub URL parsing.\n- WORKDIR in Dockerfile creates the directory, which conflicts with git clone into that path.\n\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Nothing major blocked. The 5-persona review caught 12 issues across all severity levels, validating the review process.",
